" Right Place Right Time" project for enabling NYC's middle school students¶

   PASSNYC is a not-for-profit organization that facilitates a collective impact that is dedicated to broadening educational opportunities for New York City's talented and underserved students. New York City is home to some of the most impressive educational institutions in the world, yet in recent years, the Citys specialized high schools - institutions with historically transformative impact on student outcomes - have seen a shift toward more homogeneous student body demographics.

   PASSNYC aims to increase the diversity of students taking the Specialized High School Admissions Test (SHSAT). By focusing efforts in under-performing areas that are historically underrepresented in SHSAT registration , PASSNYC hopes to pave the path to specialized high schools for a more diverse group of students.

   PASSNYC and its partners provide "outreach services" that improve the chances of students taking the SHSAT(exam) and receiving placements in these specialized high schools(SPHS). The current process of identifying schools is effective, but PASSNYC could have an even greater impact with a more informed, granular approach to quantifying the potential for outreach at a given school. Proxies that have been good indicators of these types of schools include data on English Language Learners, Students with Disabilities, Students on Free/Reduced Lunch, and Students with Temporary Housing.

   Part of this challenge is to assess the needs of students by using publicly available data to quantify the challenges they face in taking the SHSAT. The solution will enable PASSNYC to identify the schools where minority and underserved students stand to gain the most from services like after school programs, test preparation, mentoring, or resources for parents.

# 'Training_Need_Score' which is calculated as the ratio of "count of offers" received by a school to
# the total number of 8th Graders in the school will be a good indicator of the school's position in the total list of 
# middle schools and this score would help PASSNYC decide which schools to focus on, for training the capable students. 

# Similarly'Awareness_Need_Score' which is calculated as the ratio of  "count of testers" in a school to the total number 
# of 8th Graders in the school gives an idea of the popularity of the program amongst the students  and  would help PASSNYC 
# focus on eligible schools with the aim of getting more capable students to take the tests

# City  currently has two broad categories for the 'count of offers', which is '0-5' and '>5', wherein the former are currently
# underperforming schools 

shsat_1516["Year"] = '2015-16'

PASSNYC has two goals in this program. One is to identify schools(currently non-feeder schools) with academically qualified students, which would benefit from training programs.Currently, the students in these schools are taking SHSAT but without good results.

Another is to identify schools where the awareness of SHSAT is less and there are not many test takers. In such schools PASSNYC can do road shows and immersion programs to popularize the program and its benefits.

So I need to classify schools into 1) Schools that need training and those that do not need training 2) schools that need awareness programs and those that do not need such programs as of now

Need_Training_Score is calculated as the ratio of the 'number of offers received in a school' to the total number of students in the school', with a lower score indicating a for training requirement for the school.

Need_Awareness_Score is calculated as the ratio of the 'number of test takers in the school' to the ' total number of students in the school' . This gives a clear idea of how popular the program is amongst the students of the school.

These schools can be broadly categorised into Feeder schools and Non- feeder schools based on whether students get admission to SPHS from these schools or not. Feeder schools are the ones with 5 or more students qualifying in SHSAT exams and Non-Feeder schools are one with 0-5 students qualifying in SHSAT.

Below I have done a detailed data anlysis to see whether there is any relation between the demographics of these two categoroes of schools and the performance in SHSAT.

Hover above Red and Blue Dots in the map to see School Name¶

Click on circle to see Training Requirement Status¶

The above map shows the list of middle schools in NYC with 'red' icon indicating schools that would benefit from
immersion programs or road shows for awareness creation and the ones in 'blue' are the ones that dont stand ot benefit from the program in the immediate future

In this project, I have attempted to help PASSNYC in achieving its objective of increasing the diversity of student body in NYC's SPHS . My project makes very effective recommendation with the list of schools that PASSNYC needs to focus on for training as well as for popularising the program.

# Further work that can be done in future¶

1.) The list of schools can be further categorised , based on

    a) geography/ burroughs of NYC
    b) based on the average school income
    c) ela and math scores

and ranking given or grouped up , so that training plans can be tailored according to the needs of these groups.
